@node "Usage" "HTMLToTeX - Usage"
@next "Options"
@prev "Main"

 HTMLtoTeX has been designed to convert HTML text (!) documents
 taken from the WorldWideWeb to LaTeX2e documents.

 The program can not convert any type of HTML files.
 Trying to convert a web page full of graphics, applets
 and so on into LaTeX2e files is obviously useless!

 In return, HTMLtoTeX recognises the following HTML
 elements and tries to convert them to suitable LaTeX2e tags:

 · nearly all numeric and character entities

 · most common font styles (such as <B>)

 · information style elements (<CODE> for example),

 · headings (<H1>)

 · paragraphs (<P>) and linebreaks (<BR>)

 · ordered, unordered and definition lists

 · preformatted text (<PRE>), block quotes (<BQ>)

 As you see, tabulars are (currently) not supported.
 Unknown HTML tags will just be filtered out.

 HTMLtoTeX needs a minimum stack size of 20000 bytes.
 To use the program, open a shell and type the following:

    1> stack 20000
    1> HTMLtoTeX mywebtext.htm
    1> latex mywebtext.tex
    1> showdvi mywebtext.dvi

 More easier is the following way:

    1> stack 20000
    1> HTMLtoTeX mywebtext
    1> latex mywebtext
    1> showdvi mywebtext

 You can change the way the conversion is done by using
 some @{" optional arguments " link "Options" 0}.

 Since version 2 HTMLtoTeX provides a complete @{" workbench interface " link "GUI" 0}.
@endnode

@node "GUI" "HTMLtoTeX - The GUI"
@next "Options"
@prev "Usage"

 As a new feature, Version 2 of HTMLtoTeX provides a simple, but complete
 graphical user interface.

 In the window, which appears after starting HTMLtoTeX from Workbench, you
 can both choose the (HTML) source and the (LaTeX2e) target file.

 Please note that HTMLtoTeX opens an AppWindow, so you can drag one (no
 more!) icon of your HTML file and drop it over the window.

 To change the conversion @{" options " link "Options" 7}, select "Set options..." from the
 "Conversion" menu with the right mouse button.






 @{u}Note@{uu}

 The GUI has been created with new routines developed by myself to provide
a
 font sensitive window layout. These were not properly tested. So if you
 notice any errors or strange behaviour of other kind, @{i}please@{ui} let
 @{" me " link "Misc" 10} know -- thanks!
@endnode

@node "Options" "HTMLToTeX - command line options"
@next "Misc"
@prev "Usage"

 @{u}The template:@{uu}

 @{b}FROM/A,TO,HEADER,Q=QUIET/S,GERMAN/S,LINKS/S,RULES/S,PLAIN/S,BUFFER/L@{ub}


 @{u}The options:@{uu}

 @{fg shine}FROM/A@{fg text}      Your source file in HTML format.
             If the file cannot be found, HTMLtoTeX appends
             the ".htm" appendix to the filename automatically
             and tries to read it again.

 @{fg shine}TO@{fg text}          The name of the target file produced by HTMLtoTeX
             after conversion.
             If there is no filename supplied, HTMLtoTeX takes
             the one of the sourcefile and changes the
             ".htm" appendix to ".tex".

 @{fg shine}HEADER@{fg text}      HTMLtoTeX automatically produces a complete
             latex file with a @{" suitable header " link "Header" 0}.
             If you want to use your own header, use this
             option. Then, HTMLtoTeX reads the header file,
             appends the converted text and saves the
             whole file to the target file.

             @{i}Example:@{ui} HTMLToTeX Test.htm header=TeX:Text/myheader.tex

 @{fg fill}Q=QUIET/S@{fg text}   When using this option, HTMLtoTeX does not
             print any output into the CLI output stream.
             Useful within DOS scripts.

 @{fg fill}GERMAN/S@{fg text}    The option "german" will be used in the
             LaTeX2e option.

 @{fg fill}LINKS/S@{fg text}     The HTML hyperlinks will be marked in
             the latex2e textfile by using the
             {\sffamily [link]} tag.

 @{fg fill}RULES/S@{fg text}     Some HTML text documents are containing
             horicontal rules (<HR> tag). This looks
             quiet strange in latex2e documents, so
             the horicontal rules will be filtered out
             normally. If you want to keep them, you
             have to use this option.

 @{fg fill}PLAIN/S@{fg text}     By using this option, you can force HTMLtoTeX
             to convert only the pure text information.
             There won't be any style conversion.

 @{fg shine}BUFFER/N@{fg text}    The size (in KBytes) of the input filebuffer
             used while converting. The default is 10, which
             means a filebuffer of 10 KBytes.
             The larger the filebuffer, the faster the
             conversion will be. While loading the source file,
             HTMLtoTeX will print out a dot (.) every time the file
             buffer is full.
@endnode

@node "Header" "HTMLToTeX - The built-in header"
@next "Misc"
@prev "Options"

 Here you can see the built-in standard header.
 It uses the "fancyheadings" package for easy page layout control.

 You can use your own header by using the "header" @{" option " link "Options" 0}.



 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

 % Converted with HTMLtoTeX 1.00 © by Axel Sodtalbers.

 \documentclass [a4paper] {article}

 \usepackage[latin1]{inputenc}
 \usepackage{fancyheadings}
 \usepackage[T1]{fontenc}

 \pagestyle{fancy}
 \lhead{[...title...]}
 \chead{}
 \rhead{}
 \lfoot{}
 \cfoot{}
 \rfoot{}

 \parindent0pt

 \begin{document}
 \sloppy


 [...converted body...]


 \end{document}
@endnode

@node "Misc" "HTMLtoTeX - Miscellaneous, Contact"
@prev "Usage"

 @{b}@{u}Problems:@{ub}@{uu}

 Currently, there are problems with

 @{" entities " link "Problems" 0}, @{" list elements " link "Problems" 35} and @{" comments " link "Problems" 46}.



 @{b}@{u}Contact:@{ub}@{uu}

 While programming HTMLtoTeX, the aim was to write not a fast
 but a compatible code. For example all attributes of the HTML
 tags are read, but currently not processed.

 If you have any ideas, suggestions for enhancement or
 error reports, please send an email to me:

    @{fg shine}asodtal@gwdg.de@{fg text}


 @{b}@{u}Versions:@{ub}@{uu}

 1.00   - first released version

 1.10   - fixed tag reading bug
          HTML remarks (<!..>) are processed
          small workbench port added

 1.11   - proper handling of <PRE> tags

 2.00   - GUI implementated

 2.10   - GUI slightly improved, conversion progress indicator added


 @{b}@{u}Thanks to@{ub}@{uu}

 · Frederic Jacquet (for the first error report!)
 · Thomas Schraitle (found an excellent bug...!)
@endnode

@node "Problems" "HTMLToTeX - Problems (yes there are some!)"

 @{b}@{u}Problems with entities:@{ub}@{uu}

 There are some problems with the conversion of entities:

 · if a numeric entity can not be converted to a latex equivalent,
   "???CannotConvert???" will be written to the latex
   target file. Currently this is done with the following
   characters:

      "Ż" "Ş" "ş" "Ţ" "ţ"

   Does anybody know how to print these characters with LaTeX2e?

 · if the format of the numeric entity is wrong,
   "???EntityConvErr???" will be written.

 · if a character entity can not be converted,
   "???c???" will be written (c is the first character of the entity).

 · currently there are difficulties with terms like

     "blabla Sodtalbers&Partner blabla"

   The & character will be processed as the start of an entity
   which is wrong in these cases. I work on this problem.
   The & in

     "blabla Sodtalbers & Partner blabla"

   will be processed in the right way.



 @{b}@{u}Problems with list elements:@{ub}@{uu}

 Another problem: in many HTML sources you can find a
 <LI> tag outside <OL> </OL> or other list tags.
 Browsers will display a dot ("· text"), although
 - according to my sources - list elements outside list
 tag pairs are illegal.
 Nevertheless HTMLtoTeX will convert *every* <LI> to \item.
 This may cause some errors in the latex file.


 @{b}@{u}Problems with comments:@{ub}@{uu}

 Do not write HTML tags within comments,
 this will confuse HTMLtoTeX!
@endnode

